":"1485","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","about 1441":"circa 1441","1439":"1439","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Saint Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"St Clement, Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1419–1443":"1419–1443","1421–1485":"1421–1485","1439–1489":"1439–1489","1441–1520":"1441–1520","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1400–1425":"1400–1425","17 September 1425":"17 September 1425","1425":"1425","1489":"1489","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1520":"1520","1421":"1421","1441":"1441","1485":"1485","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","about 1441":"about 1441","1439":"1439","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Saint Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"St Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom",", England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clement","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alcide, Alphonse, Andre, Marcel, Armand, Cecile, Christophe, Gaston, Olivier, Aime.","English, Catalan, German, Flemish, and Dutch; French and Walloon (<b>Clément</b>): from the Latin personal name <i>Clemens</i> meaning ‘merciful’ (genitive <i>Clementis</i>). This achieved popularity firstly through having been borne by an early Christian saint who was a disciple of Saint Paul, and later because it was selected as a symbolic name by a number of early popes. There has also been some confusion with the personal name <i>Clemence</i> (from Latin <i>Clementia</i>, meaning ‘mercy’, an abstract noun derived from the adjective; in part a masculine name from Latin <i>Clementius</i>, a later derivative of <i>Clemens</i>). In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, especially Italian   Clemente  , and also their derivatives."],"variants":[{"name":"Clem","meanings":["English (Somerset): from a short form of the personal name   Clement   or of the female form, <i>Clemence</i>.","Americanized form of German <b>Klemm</b> and German or Dutch <b>Klem</b>: from a short form of the personal name   Klemens  ."]},{"name":"Clements","meanings":["English, Irish (Tyrone and Antrim), and Dutch: variant of   Clement  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. In North America, this surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, e.g. German   Clementz   and Slovenian patronymic <b>Klemenc</b> (see   Klements  )."]},{"name":"Clemente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Elia, Manuel, Cesar, Fernando, Luis, Rafael, Alfredo, Andres, Armando, Gerardo.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Salvatore, Vito, Gino, Angelo, Nicola, Rocco, Enrico, Guido, Marco, Matteo.  Portuguese Joaquim.","Spanish, Italian, and Portuguese: from the personal name<i>Clemente</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Crimi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Gaetano, Vita, Cosimo, Giuseppe, Luciano, Luigi, Sal, Tommaso.","Italian (Sicily): from an altered form of the medieval Greek personal name <i>Klēmēs</i>, from Latin <i>Clemens</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Chimenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Angelo, Francesco, Filomena, Guido.","Italian (southern): variant of <b>Clementi</b> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clemon","meanings":["English: probably from a variant of the personal name   Clement  .","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish and northern Irish   McClymont  ."]},{"name":"Klehm","meanings":["North German: from a short form of the personal name <i>Klement</i> (see   Clement  )."]},{"name":"Clementson","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Clement   + <i>-son</i>. See also   Clements   and   Clemson  .","Americanized form of Swedish <b>Klementsson</b> or <b>Clementsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name <i>Klement</i>,   Clement  .","Americanized form of Danish and Norwegian <b>Clementsen</b> or <b>Klementsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."]},{"name":"Kelemen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Andras, Gabor, Geza, Imre, Laszlo, Tibor, Bela, Gyula, Istvan, Jozsef, Karoly, Leszlo.","Hungarian, Croatian, Slovak, Rusyn, and Slovenian: from the personal name <i>Kelemen</i>, Hungarian form of   Clement  . The Hungarian surname is also common in Romania."]},{"name":"Climie","meanings":["Scottish: from a Scots pet form of the personal name   Clement  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Clement I was born in 1419, in Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, John Clement, was 63 and his mother, Joan Montague, was 19. He married Mabel ferch Gruffud in 1439, in Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1443, in St Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 24, and was buried in Wales."},"et":{"1419–1443":"1419–1443","1421–1485":"1421–1485","1439–1489":"1439–1489","1441–1520":"1441–1520","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1400–1425":"1400–1425","17 September 1425":"17. september 1425","1425":"1425","1489":"1489","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1520":"1520","1421":"1421","1441":"1441","1485":"1485","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","about 1441":"umbes 1441","1439":"1439","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Saint Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"St Clement, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1419–1443":"1419–1443","1421–1485":"1421–1485","1439–1489":"1439–1489","1441–1520":"1441–1520","1356–1429":"1356–1429","1400–1425":"1400–1425","17 September 1425":"17. syyskuuta 1425","1425":"1425","1489":"1489","1400":"1400","1356":"1356","1443":"1443","1520":"1520","1421":"1421","1441":"1441","1485":"1485","1419":"1419","1429":"1429","about 1441":"noin 1441","1439":"1439","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Caron-uwch-clawdd, Cardiganshire, Wales"," Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Cardiganshire, Wales":"Cardiganshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","Saint Clement, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"St Clement, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",", England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1419–1443":"1419–1443","1421–1485":"1421–1485","1439–1489":"1439–1489","144